      <hedline>
        <hl1>RED SEA DIVE</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan S Blaustein letter on April 8 travel article on scuba diving in Red Sea off Egypt</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: ''Egypt: On the Red Sea, As Hotels Go Up, Divers Head Down'' (Explorer, April 8) looked like one of those ''What Went Wrong'' post-mortems used for education in diver magazines. The reporter acknowledged his limited diving experience and then broke three cardinal rules of dive safety.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: ''Egypt: On the Red Sea, As Hotels Go Up, Divers Head Down'' (Explorer, April 8) looked like one of those ''What Went Wrong'' post-mortems used for education in diver magazines. The reporter acknowledged his limited diving experience and then broke three cardinal rules of dive safety.</p>
        <p>First, he should have been aware of his diminishing air supply before he needed to share the guide's secondary air source. Second, when he did use the guide's secondary air source, he should have, along with the guide, made a safe ascent immediately. Finally, and especially being aware of his limitations, he should not have entered a cave on a later dive. Fortunately, he did not have any problems inside the cave. Without specialty training, this can be a dangerous undertaking.</p>
        <p>Scuba diving, when done properly and safely, as trained, is a very safe, enjoyable, and even relaxing sport.</p>
        <p>Alan S. Blaustein  Los Angeles</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
